04482nam a22005175i 9780887554575DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875545757 a10.1515/97808875545752doi  a(DE-B1597)665282  a(OCoLC)1027127440  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 7aHIS0280002bisacsh04a971.3/40049755qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aHill, Susan M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Clay We Are Made Of :bHaudenosaunee Land Tenure on the Grand River /cSusan M. Hill. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Studies in Native History ;v2000tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgements -- tThe Clay We Are Made Of -- tHaudenosaunee Cultural History and Relationship to Land -- tKarihwa’onwe—The Original Matters -- tKontinonhsyonni—The Women Who Make the House -- tHaudenosaunee Land Tenure: From Iroquoia to the Grand River Territory -- tTeyohahá:KE—Two Roads -- tShotinonhsyonnih—They Built the Longhouse Again -- tSkanata Yoyonnih—One Village Has Been Made -- tTe Yonkhi’nikònhare Tsi Niyonkwarihotenhs— They Are Interfering in Our Matters -- tTetitewennonhtonhstha Tsi Niyonkwarihotenhs— We Are Causing Ourselves to Have Control Again, the Way We Do Things -- tSix Nations Censuses -- tSix Nations Claims Filed with the Specific Claims Branch -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIf one seeks to understand Haudenosaunee (Six Nations) history, one must consider the history of Haudenosaunee land. For countless generations prior to European contact, land and territory informed Haudenosaunee thought and philosophy, and was a primary determinant of Haudenosaunee identity. In The Clay We Are Made Of, Susan M. Hill presents a revolutionary retelling of the history of the Grand River Haudenosaunee from their Creation Story through European contact to contemporary land claims negotiations. She incorporates Indigenous theory, fourth world post-colonialism, and Amerindian autohistory, along with Haudenosaunee languages, oral records, and wampum strings to provide the most comprehensive account of the Haudenosaunee’s relationship to their land. Hill outlines the basic principles and historical knowledge contained within four key epics passed down through Haudenosaunee cultural history. She highlights the political role of women in land negotiations and dispels their misrepresentation in the scholarly canon. She guides the reader through treaty relationships with Dutch, French, and British settler nations, including the Kaswentha/Two-Row Wampum (the precursor to all future Haudenosaunee-European treaties), the Covenant Chain, the Nanfan Treaty, and the Haldimand Proclamation, and concludes with a discussion of the current problematic relationships between the Grand River Haudenosaunee, the Crown, and the Canadian government.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh  aHaudenosaunee, Iroquois, Six Nations, Grand River, First Nations, Land Claims,.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755457540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887554575423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887554575/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles